:QUOTE
A twenty-five dollar USB stick and a coat hanger wire can receive photographs from space.

:INFO
What NOAA APT Satellites Transmit
NOAA 15, 18, and 19 are polar-orbiting weather satellites that continuously broadcast images on 137 MHz in a format called APT (Automatic Picture Transmission). The signal is analog FM and can be received with a simple omnidirectional antenna. Each satellite passes overhead 2 to 4 times per day at a peak elevation visible for about 10 minutes. Free software decodes the audio recording into a visible weather image.

:COUNTER.half
137.1 / 137.9 MHz
NOAA 18 and 19 downlink frequencies — check for current frequencies
|
:COUNTER.half
10 to 15 Minutes
Pass duration above the horizon for a useful signal

:PATH
Set Up the RTL-SDR and Drivers
Install RTL-SDR drivers and verify the dongle works with SDR#.
|
:INFO
Set Up the RTL-SDR and Drivers
Purchase an RTL-SDR Blog V4 dongle — better shielding than cheaper clones. Install Zadig driver on Windows: run Zadig, select the RTL-SDR device, install WinUSB driver. Open SDR# (sdrsharp.com) and tune to an FM radio station to verify reception. You should hear clear audio. Linux: rtl-sdr driver installs via apt.

:PATH
Build or Connect a V-Dipole Antenna
Two elements each 53.5cm long at 120 degrees apart — tuned for 137 MHz.
|
:INFO
Build or Connect a V-Dipole Antenna
A V-dipole antenna tuned to 137 MHz requires two elements each 53.5cm long. Angle them at 120 degrees from each other (not 180 degrees). Connect to coax with one element to center and one to shield. Mount pointing upward, horizontally polarized. The RTL-SDR Blog dipole kit ($10) includes adjustable elements and is the easiest solution.

:PATH
Find Pass Times and Record the Signal
Use Heavens-Above or Orbitron to predict passes and record with SDR#.
|
:INFO
Find Pass Times and Record the Signal
Use Heavens-Above.com (enter your location) or Orbitron to predict NOAA satellite passes. Look for passes above 30° maximum elevation — low passes produce weak signals. Set SDR# to the satellite frequency (NFM mode, ~40kHz bandwidth) 1 to 2 minutes before the pass. Record the audio pass using Audacity or SDR#'s built-in recorder as a WAV file at 44100 Hz.

:PATH
Decode the Recorded Audio Into an Image
Open the WAV file in NOAA APT decoder software to extract the image.
|
:INFO
Decode the Recorded Audio Into an Image
Open your recorded WAV file in WXtoImg (historical but still widely used) or the open-source noaa-apt software. The software decodes the audio modulation into two side-by-side infrared images showing cloud cover, land surface temperature, and geographic features. The image quality correlates directly with antenna placement and maximum elevation of the pass.

:CHECKLIST
What You Need
[ ] RTL-SDR Blog V4 USB dongle
[ ] V-dipole antenna kit or DIY from wire
[ ] SDR# or SDR++ software (Windows) or GQRX (Linux/Mac)
[ ] noaa-apt or WXtoImg decoding software
[ ] Heavens-Above.com account for pass prediction

:NOTE
Doppler Shift Degrades Long Passes
As the satellite approaches, its frequency appears slightly higher than nominal, then shifts lower as it moves away. WXtoImg handles Doppler correction automatically if you configure your location. noaa-apt also has Doppler correction. Manual recordings at a fixed frequency will show a slight audio pitch variation — this is normal and does not prevent decoding.

:QUOTE
An image of cloud cover over your continent, received by hardware you assembled yourself. That is not a simulation.

